The Hagakure says in the past all samurai would bathe, shave, trim their nails every morning to be ready to die that day. If you die unseemly you were not prepared to die that day. Any time you shower, clip your nails, etc. you should see it as this mortuary, death-affirming act.

E.g. baptism, unction all resemble rites performed on a death body in preparation for burial. Both Bushido and Christianity consist in treating your body as already dead in preparation for death. You always have your death in your mind and anything you do is to harden ur resolve.

A lack of cleanliness in a corpse shows a lack of resolve to die. When you bathe and lotion your hair, you are treating your body like a cadaver. It softens the body, but hardens the resolve to die. Dmitry Galkovsky believes all Christian rites originated in mortuary sect rituals
